10:59.951 --> 11:01.661
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:01.661 --> 11:04.539
<i>‐ The guts of the axe‐head</i>
<i>are spreading.</i>

11:04.539 --> 11:06.207
And every time
I try to close it, it‐‐

11:06.207 --> 11:07.834
just springs back open.

11:07.834 --> 11:11.254
‐ I'd be surprised if all
of those welds are pretty.

11:11.254 --> 11:14.215
<i>‐ No time to start over</i>
<i>whatsoever.</i>

11:14.215 --> 11:18.094
<i>I decided that I would</i>
<i>grind away what I didn't need</i>

11:18.094 --> 11:21.848
and then
weld the seams together.

11:21.848 --> 11:25.018
‐ You have 30 minutes remaining
to finish your blades!

11:25.018 --> 11:26.644
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:26.644 --> 11:30.398
‐ I've got some delams
on the edge of my axe‐head.

11:30.398 --> 11:33.109
<i>But I don't think that</i>
<i>heating them</i>

11:33.109 --> 11:36.863
<i>and power‐hammering them</i>
<i>will get me anything more.</i>

11:36.863 --> 11:40.408
<i>I'm gonna try to clean up</i>
<i>what I have, quench it,</i>

11:40.408 --> 11:43.703
and turn in
a functioning axe‐head.

11:43.703 --> 11:45.830
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:45.830 --> 11:47.874
‐ Do you hear that sound?
‐ Yeah.

11:47.874 --> 11:50.460
‐ That's an unwelded piece
of metal being ground.

11:50.460 --> 11:52.754
<i>[intense music]</i>

11:52.754 --> 11:54.297
‐ The quench
is always nerve‐racking

11:54.297 --> 11:56.591
especially‐‐I used mild steel

11:56.591 --> 12:00.053
<i>and forge weld</i>
<i>a high‐carbon steel to it.</i>

12:00.053 --> 12:02.263
The mild steel will shrink
at a different rate

12:02.263 --> 12:04.265
than the high‐carbon steel,
so if the forge welds

12:04.265 --> 12:07.560
aren't perfect,
it could just rip itself apart.

12:07.560 --> 12:09.020
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:09.020 --> 12:10.563
This is gonna take
a lot longer

12:10.563 --> 12:12.106
to heat up than the edge.

12:12.106 --> 12:13.775
<i>I'll be able to heat up</i>
<i>the spike separately,</i>

12:13.775 --> 12:16.236
<i>quench it, then heat up</i>
<i>the edge separately</i>

12:16.236 --> 12:18.363
<i>and quench it.</i>

12:18.363 --> 12:20.406
‐ Did Jason just quench?
‐ He quenched the spike,

12:20.406 --> 12:22.533
which is smart because you can
keep that out of the way

12:22.533 --> 12:24.244
of the fire
when you do the blade.

12:24.244 --> 12:25.828
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:25.828 --> 12:27.664
<i>‐ Got a pretty</i>
<i>good‐looking blade</i>

12:27.664 --> 12:29.290
<i>over here coming out of Seth.</i>

12:29.290 --> 12:30.583
‐ All of a sudden Seth‐‐

12:30.583 --> 12:32.919
‐ Just magically appeared
out of nowhere.

12:32.919 --> 12:36.256
‐ I was feeling behind
but caught up to myself.

12:36.256 --> 12:39.259
<i>I'm seeing good, solid welds</i>
<i>along the edge.</i>

12:39.259 --> 12:40.718
Let's get it quenched.

12:40.718 --> 12:42.095
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:42.095 --> 12:44.097
‐ Seth is in.
‐ With a very, very hot‐‐

12:44.097 --> 12:46.766
‐ Whoa. Fireballs.
‐ Let it stay, man.

12:46.766 --> 12:48.768
‐ Everything looks
good and straight.

12:48.768 --> 12:50.186
Whoo‐hoo!

12:50.186 --> 12:52.105
<i>This thing ought to be</i>
<i>pretty bad ass.</i>

12:52.105 --> 12:53.815
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:53.815 --> 12:55.483
<i>‐ Over here, Joe,</i>

12:55.483 --> 12:57.277
hopefully
he can turn this around.

12:57.277 --> 12:58.695
<i>‐ I definitely hit a wall</i>

12:58.695 --> 13:00.530
<i>trying to widen out</i>
<i>that axe‐head.</i>

13:00.530 --> 13:03.658
I'm exhausted.
Feeling the heat right now.

13:03.658 --> 13:06.035
I'm gonna quickly quench this,
that way I can at least

13:06.035 --> 13:08.788
get a hardened axe‐head
and a hardened spike.

13:08.788 --> 13:10.623
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:10.623 --> 13:13.042
This is not an ideal scenario
at all.

13:13.042 --> 13:15.003
<i>I only have seconds left</i>
<i>and I'm trying to get</i>

13:15.003 --> 13:17.672
<i>this axe‐head and this spike</i>
<i>welded together.</i>

13:17.672 --> 13:19.465
<i>I'm doing</i>
<i>everything I can</i>

13:19.465 --> 13:21.134
<i>just to at least</i>
<i>turn something in.</i>

13:21.134 --> 13:23.219
I'm not gonna give up.

13:23.219 --> 13:27.890
‐ Five, four,
three, two, one!

13:27.890 --> 13:30.643
Drop your tools!
Shut down your machines!

13:30.643 --> 13:32.270
This round is over!

13:32.270 --> 13:33.730
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:33.730 --> 13:36.316
<i>‐ I've done</i>
<i>everything I could do</i>

13:36.316 --> 13:40.737
and it's up to the judges
and the pirate gods right now.

13:40.737 --> 13:45.491
I don't wanna walk the plank
because I swim like a stone.

13:45.491 --> 13:47.326
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:47.326 --> 13:50.663
‐ Bladesmiths,
taking that pirate's treasure

13:50.663 --> 13:52.790
and turning them
into fully functional

13:52.790 --> 13:53.916
boarding axes?

13:53.916 --> 13:55.710
I mean, that's
a hell of a task.

13:55.710 --> 13:58.671
Now it's time for the judges
to take a closer look.

13:58.671 --> 14:00.506
Seth.
You're up first.

14:00.506 --> 14:02.633
Please present
your blade to the judges.

14:02.633 --> 14:04.218
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:04.218 --> 14:06.262
<i>‐ Right off, it's light.</i>

14:06.262 --> 14:09.182
<i>This is gonna make something</i>
<i>that you can actually wield</i>

14:09.182 --> 14:12.393
as opposed to a boat anchor
with an edge on it.

14:12.393 --> 14:14.604
The spike is wicked.

14:14.604 --> 14:17.523
The only issue I really have is

14:17.523 --> 14:20.026
are the outside edges
of your blade,

14:20.026 --> 14:22.528
<i>that mild steel goes</i>
<i>all the way to the edge</i>

14:22.528 --> 14:23.821
<i>on one side.</i>

14:23.821 --> 14:25.364
And it doesn't
on the other side.

14:25.364 --> 14:27.033
So I'm sure
you could grind that down

14:27.033 --> 14:28.993
to where that
hardenable steel is

14:28.993 --> 14:32.413
so that entire edge
is that hard steel.

14:32.413 --> 14:33.956
‐ All right, Jason, you're up.

14:33.956 --> 14:36.209
Please present your
boarding axe to the judges.

14:36.209 --> 14:37.710
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:37.710 --> 14:40.171
<i>‐ What I'd love to see</i>
<i>is some refinement.</i>

14:40.171 --> 14:42.715
<i>Refine that spike,</i>
<i>clean out that eye</i>

14:42.715 --> 14:43.925
<i>so you can get</i>
<i>a good fit to</i>

14:43.925 --> 14:45.468
whatever half you put on here.

14:45.468 --> 14:49.222
But this is all
good, solid hard steel up here

14:49.222 --> 14:51.349
which is great.
‐ Thank you.

14:51.349 --> 14:53.810
‐ It's not just utilitarian
but it's really combative

14:53.810 --> 14:55.103
with the things
that you can do with this,

14:55.103 --> 14:56.896
with the hooking features
of this.

14:56.896 --> 15:00.316
Definitely it's a boarding axe
that I can just do wonders.

15:00.316 --> 15:02.401
I like it.
[soft laugh]

15:02.401 --> 15:04.070
‐ All right, Stephen,
you're up.

15:04.070 --> 15:06.531
Please present your
boarding axe to the judges.

15:06.531 --> 15:07.907
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:07.907 --> 15:10.326
<i>‐ It's quite rough‐looking.</i>

15:10.326 --> 15:13.079
<i>It's got a lot of gaps</i>
<i>in the forge welds here.</i>

15:13.079 --> 15:16.749
In the spike here it's held on
by MIG welding on one side

15:16.749 --> 15:18.751
and there's not really anything
on the other side

15:18.751 --> 15:20.253
holding it together.

15:20.253 --> 15:21.629
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:21.629 --> 15:23.464
[metal clicking]
‐ Something in there is loose.

15:23.464 --> 15:26.676
If you move forward with this,
might wanna think about

15:26.676 --> 15:28.302
filling in some of those welds.

15:28.302 --> 15:31.597
Clean it and fill it.
‐ Yes, sir.

15:31.597 --> 15:33.099
‐ All right, Joseph.

15:33.099 --> 15:35.101
Please present your
boarding axe to the judges.

15:35.101 --> 15:36.936
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:36.936 --> 15:40.273
<i>‐ Unfortunately, I don't know</i>
<i>how to judge this as an axe.</i>

15:40.273 --> 15:42.608
<i>There's no eye at all.</i>

15:42.608 --> 15:46.112
The blade is
kind of spatulate

15:46.112 --> 15:48.865
instead of being axe‐shaped.

15:48.865 --> 15:52.118
It does have a spike,
but it's held on by

15:52.118 --> 15:54.495
<i>a couple of dots of MIG weld.</i>

15:54.495 --> 15:57.248
I mean, I could probably
just snap this right now.

15:57.248 --> 16:02.962
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:02.962 --> 16:06.966
‐ Joseph, your steel has met
none of the parameters

16:06.966 --> 16:09.177
that we laid out
for a pirate boarding axe

16:09.177 --> 16:12.305
and you can't move forward
in this competition.

16:12.305 --> 16:14.390
However,
listen, little brother,

16:14.390 --> 16:17.643
you show a lot of moxie,
a lot of initiative.

16:17.643 --> 16:19.812
Unfortunately
in this round of competition,

16:19.812 --> 16:21.981
I have to ask you
to please leave The Forge.

16:21.981 --> 16:23.649
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:23.649 --> 16:25.818
‐ I do agree
with the judges' decision.

16:25.818 --> 16:28.070
My blade definitely
was not up to par.

16:28.070 --> 16:29.488
‐ Good luck.

16:29.488 --> 16:31.657
<i>‐ This competition</i>
<i>is definitely tough.</i>

16:31.657 --> 16:33.075
<i>But I never quit.</i>

16:33.075 --> 16:34.702
<i>I made sure</i>
<i>I turned something in.</i>

16:34.702 --> 16:36.621
If I could do it over again,
I definitely would.

16:36.621 --> 16:39.582
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:39.582 --> 16:41.292
‐ All right, bladesmiths,
congratulations.

16:41.292 --> 16:42.877
You've made it
to the second round

16:42.877 --> 16:44.212
of this competition.

16:44.212 --> 16:45.671
Now that your blades
have been tempered

16:45.671 --> 16:47.340
you must attach handles
to those blades,

16:47.340 --> 16:48.841
turning them into
fully‐functional

16:48.841 --> 16:50.509
pirates boarding axes.

16:50.509 --> 16:54.472
<i>You must also include langets</i>
<i>on each side of your axe</i>

16:54.472 --> 16:57.183
<i>that are measured at least</i>
<i>five inches in length</i>

16:57.183 --> 17:00.645
<i>from the bottom of the socket</i>
<i>to the bottom of the langet.</i>

17:00.645 --> 17:03.814
Since pirates were
the original bling kings,

17:03.814 --> 17:06.317
you must incorporate
at least one element

17:06.317 --> 17:09.528
from that treasure chest
into your boarding axe's

17:09.528 --> 17:11.447
overall finished design.

17:11.447 --> 17:12.990
Make it pop.

17:12.990 --> 17:15.451
Make it something that a pirate
would want to steal.

17:15.451 --> 17:18.412
After this round your weapons
will be tested for strength

17:18.412 --> 17:21.874
and durability
in a treasure chest chop

17:21.874 --> 17:25.169
and for edge retention
in a rope slice.

17:25.169 --> 17:26.212
Good luck, bladesmiths.

17:26.212 --> 17:28.881
Your three hours starts...

17:28.881 --> 17:30.716
now.

17:30.716 --> 17:33.094
All of our bladesmiths
have an incredible amount

17:33.094 --> 17:34.387
of work to do.

17:34.387 --> 17:36.514
How do these guys
attach the langets?

17:36.514 --> 17:38.808
‐ My bet is they're all three
gonna MIG weld them on.

17:38.808 --> 17:40.601
‐ That's the easiest way to go.

17:40.601 --> 17:43.437
Though it might be smart
to actually wrap them up

17:43.437 --> 17:45.731
and over the top
of their entire head

17:45.731 --> 17:47.567
and pin them through.

17:47.567 --> 17:51.737
‐ The langets keeps that weapon
attached to that stick.

17:51.737 --> 17:53.406
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:53.406 --> 17:55.074
<i>‐ I don't really like</i>
<i>the welder.</i>

17:55.074 --> 17:57.034
I don't think it likes me,

17:57.034 --> 18:00.496
<i>but I've got to do</i>
<i>some welding and fix it.</i>

18:00.496 --> 18:02.164
‐ It's a big handicap for Steve

18:02.164 --> 18:04.834
if he doesn't have
the welding skills.

18:04.834 --> 18:07.086
The nozzle is too far away
so you're just

18:07.086 --> 18:08.921
not getting
a deep penetrating weld.

18:08.921 --> 18:10.840
You get popcorn welding.

18:10.840 --> 18:12.758
It looks like
a pile of popcorn.

18:12.758 --> 18:14.343
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:14.343 --> 18:16.470
‐ My plan for this round
is to address

18:16.470 --> 18:18.931
the judges' concerns first.

18:18.931 --> 18:21.183
<i>The blade of the axe</i>
<i>is a little rough.</i>

18:21.183 --> 18:23.269
<i>I need to do</i>
<i>some finish work on it.</i>

18:23.269 --> 18:25.104
Refine the shape a little bit.

18:25.104 --> 18:27.690
<i>Eye needed to be cleaned up.</i>

18:27.690 --> 18:30.443
‐ Jason, his socket,
it's not open, it's not even.

18:30.443 --> 18:32.528
So he really needs
to clean that inside up

18:32.528 --> 18:34.780
so he can get
the shaft of that axe

18:34.780 --> 18:36.407
fitted up nice and tight.

18:36.407 --> 18:38.284
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:38.284 --> 18:40.786
<i>‐ I'm really happy</i>
<i>that they liked my design</i>

18:40.786 --> 18:43.331
but I've got the langets
ahead of me.

18:43.331 --> 18:45.625
<i>I've gotta clean</i>
<i>the mild steel off the edge.</i>

18:45.625 --> 18:48.961
Gotta make sure
I get a good, solid mount

18:48.961 --> 18:51.297
<i>of the blade to the handle.</i>

18:51.297 --> 18:52.882
There's a lot of work ahead.

18:52.882 --> 18:54.467
‐ So what kind of handle shapes
are we gonna see?

18:54.467 --> 18:57.094
Straight handles?
Curved handles?

18:57.094 --> 18:58.721
‐ Traditionally,
they were straight.

18:58.721 --> 19:01.349
‐ But usually that wood
either flared or came down

19:01.349 --> 19:02.975
so if you were
hanging on that thing

19:02.975 --> 19:04.560
you weren't just
sliding off of it.

19:04.560 --> 19:06.562
‐ You have just
two hours remaining

19:06.562 --> 19:08.814
to finish your work!

19:08.814 --> 19:13.027
Stephen's cutting across
the grain with the sander.

19:13.027 --> 19:16.238
It's like scoring your wood
to snap right there.

19:16.238 --> 19:17.657
‐ Yeah, there're stress rises

19:17.657 --> 19:19.325
just like they are on metal.
‐ Yeah.

19:19.325 --> 19:21.577
Stephen mixed up some epoxy.

19:21.577 --> 19:24.705
‐ That's okay but‐‐
‐ No. It's not okay.

19:24.705 --> 19:26.332
‐ He hasn't attached
his langet yet.

19:26.332 --> 19:29.335
‐ There you go.
That's why it's not okay.

19:29.335 --> 19:31.253
Well done langet,
actually sits flush

19:31.253 --> 19:33.214
with the handle of the wood.
‐ Yeah, that should be

19:33.214 --> 19:35.216
a flat on the side.
‐ Exactly.

19:35.216 --> 19:37.343
<i>‐ Gonna start working on</i>
<i>the langets now.</i>

19:37.343 --> 19:39.679
They're not gonna be
really fancy

19:39.679 --> 19:42.348
but they're gonna be
squared up tight to the edge.

19:42.348 --> 19:45.101
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:45.101 --> 19:47.103
<i>‐ I think it's time to start</i>
<i>shaping the handle</i>

19:47.103 --> 19:49.689
<i>because I know</i>
<i>that's gonna take a long time.</i>

19:49.689 --> 19:51.065
It's a big hunk of wood.

19:51.065 --> 19:52.858
Right now I'm most worried
about the clock.

19:52.858 --> 19:54.276
I never know...

19:54.276 --> 19:56.070
if there's gonna be
enough time.

19:56.070 --> 19:58.447
<i>That handle</i>
<i>has to be comfortable.</i>

19:58.447 --> 19:59.865
It has to be functional.

19:59.865 --> 20:02.368
And you can't
take shortcuts on that.

20:02.368 --> 20:03.703
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:03.703 --> 20:05.538
Looking really beautiful.

20:05.538 --> 20:07.248
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:07.248 --> 20:09.041
<i>‐ I've got my handle fitted.</i>

20:09.041 --> 20:11.377
<i>Now I'm gonna</i>
<i>attach these langets.</i>

20:11.377 --> 20:13.629
I'm hoping that the langets
help keep

20:13.629 --> 20:16.882
the transition portion strong.
[bleep]

20:16.882 --> 20:19.343
<i>I realize that I welded</i>
<i>one of them on crooked.</i>

20:19.343 --> 20:23.347
‐ Seth's langets are favoring
the spine of that handle.

20:23.347 --> 20:25.433
‐ That's not good.
Our tests are brutal.

20:25.433 --> 20:27.226
If the langets
aren't properly centered,

20:27.226 --> 20:29.395
it'll be easier for them
to separate from the handle.

20:29.395 --> 20:32.606
50% possibility that
that axe will survive.

20:32.606 --> 20:34.900
<i>‐ I think they're gonna</i>
<i>separate from the wood.</i>

20:34.900 --> 20:36.527
I don't want to see
it fly off, man.

20:36.527 --> 20:38.070
That would be heartbreaking.

20:38.070 --> 20:39.822
<i>I do believe it will be</i>
<i>a critical issue.</i>

20:43.868 --> 20:45.661
<i>‐ Right after</i>
<i>I welded my langets on,</i>

20:45.661 --> 20:48.748
I realized that I welded
one of them on crooked.

20:48.748 --> 20:51.917
‐‐ Without the flush langet,
that's easy to snap that head

20:51.917 --> 20:53.252
right off it.
‐ Yeah.

20:53.252 --> 20:54.920
‐ I don't want to see
it fly off, man.

20:54.920 --> 20:56.255
That'd be heartbreaking.

20:56.255 --> 20:58.382
<i>There's not enough time</i>
<i>to restart this</i>

20:58.382 --> 21:00.050
<i>so I'm gonna</i>
<i>stick them on there</i>

21:00.050 --> 21:01.594
<i>with as much glue as possible</i>

21:01.594 --> 21:03.304
so that hopefully
it'll stay together.

21:03.304 --> 21:06.807
‐ You have 30 minutes remaining
to finish your work!

21:06.807 --> 21:08.267
<i>‐ My plan for the langets,</i>

21:08.267 --> 21:10.102
<i>I'm gonna try</i>
<i>tack welding them</i>

21:10.102 --> 21:11.937
<i>along the bottom of the axe</i>

21:11.937 --> 21:13.647
and then pin them
to the handle.

21:13.647 --> 21:16.233
And then I'm gonna incorporate
the coin on the handle.

21:16.233 --> 21:17.777
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:17.777 --> 21:19.820
<i>The thing that's taking time</i>
<i>with the langets</i>

21:19.820 --> 21:22.114
is I'm doing
each one individually.

21:22.114 --> 21:25.242
If I had just taken a clamp
and clamped them together

21:25.242 --> 21:27.828
<i>and ground them both</i>
<i>at the same time,</i>

21:27.828 --> 21:29.413
<i>I would have gotten them</i>
<i>to the same shape</i>

21:29.413 --> 21:31.415
<i>in exactly</i>
<i>the same amount of time</i>

21:31.415 --> 21:34.752
but that's me
not planning properly.

21:34.752 --> 21:36.212
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:36.212 --> 21:37.630
<i>‐ This is pretty cool.</i>

21:37.630 --> 21:39.298
We have to put treasure
on our weapons

21:39.298 --> 21:41.967
which is something
pirates actually did.

21:41.967 --> 21:45.304
‐ What is that?
‐ He's making a nail.

21:45.304 --> 21:49.517
<i>‐ I've got a steel key</i>
<i>going through a langet.</i>

21:49.517 --> 21:50.810
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:50.810 --> 21:53.229
<i>It feels solid</i>
<i>so I'm hoping that</i>

21:53.229 --> 21:55.147
<i>it hold together</i>
<i>during testing.</i>

21:55.147 --> 21:59.109
‐ You know what I like about
a guy who comes and struggles?

21:59.109 --> 22:01.612
Sometimes they come up
with fixes to problems

22:01.612 --> 22:03.489
that we never would have
thought of.

22:03.489 --> 22:04.865
‐ Yeah.

22:04.865 --> 22:07.159
‐ The way I'm gonna
incorporate my coins

22:07.159 --> 22:09.954
from the treasure chest
is to inset them

22:09.954 --> 22:11.705
behind these holes

22:11.705 --> 22:13.833
<i>and put some pins</i>
<i>in there to hold 'em solid.</i>

22:13.833 --> 22:15.751
<i>Almost like a spacer</i>
<i>in there with the coins.</i>

22:15.751 --> 22:19.505
<i>That way, it does not mess</i>
<i>with the functional integrity</i>

22:19.505 --> 22:21.465
<i>of the handle itself.</i>

22:21.465 --> 22:22.842
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:22.842 --> 22:27.346
‐ Five, four,
three, two, one!

22:27.346 --> 22:30.140
Bladesmiths,
drop what you're doing.

22:30.140 --> 22:32.142
This handle round is over.

22:32.142 --> 22:33.310
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:33.310 --> 22:34.353
‐ It just hit me.

22:34.353 --> 22:36.313
I've got a one in three chance

22:36.313 --> 22:38.482
at winning $10,000.

22:38.482 --> 22:40.234
<i>Now I just have to</i>
<i>get through the testing</i>

22:40.234 --> 22:42.987
and hopefully my axe
doesn't explode.

22:42.987 --> 22:45.865
‐ Bladesmiths,
welcome to the strength test.

22:45.865 --> 22:47.658
The treasure chest chop.

22:47.658 --> 22:49.326
There's treasure
in those treasure chests

22:49.326 --> 22:50.786
and the only tools
I have to get it out

22:50.786 --> 22:52.830
are your boarding axes.

22:52.830 --> 22:54.707
This test is all about
what happens to your axes

22:54.707 --> 22:57.334
and not what happens
to the treasure chests.

22:57.334 --> 23:00.045
Jason, you're up first.
Are you ready?

23:00.045 --> 23:01.839
‐ Let's get some treasure.

23:01.839 --> 23:03.340
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:03.340 --> 23:04.592
<i>There's a part of me</i>
<i>that's really excited</i>

23:04.592 --> 23:06.135
<i>to see what my axe can do.</i>

23:06.135 --> 23:08.012
<i>There's a bigger part of me</i>
<i>that says</i>

23:08.012 --> 23:09.555
<i>this thing's gonna fly apart</i>

23:09.555 --> 23:11.932
the minute
he hits that chest.

23:11.932 --> 23:16.687
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:16.687 --> 23:20.024
<i>[heavy metal music]</i>

23:20.024 --> 23:26.947
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:31.952 --> 23:33.787
[coins clattering]

23:34.955 --> 23:36.790
<i>[tense music]</i>

23:36.790 --> 23:39.084
‐ Man, that was fun.
‐ [laughs]

23:39.084 --> 23:41.921
‐ So the handle's
very comfortable.

23:41.921 --> 23:43.672
The one issue
is there's a flat

23:43.672 --> 23:46.842
that I can comfortably
rub my thumb across.

23:46.842 --> 23:49.428
The rest of your axe
is pretty darn sharp.

23:49.428 --> 23:51.931
The spike is perfect.

23:51.931 --> 23:54.058
Very well done.
‐ Thank you, sir.

23:54.058 --> 23:55.476
‐ Stephen, you're up next.
You ready?

23:55.476 --> 23:57.895
‐ I'm ready.
‐ Arrr‐‐right then.

23:57.895 --> 24:04.818
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:06.236 --> 24:08.822
<i>[heavy metal music]</i>

24:08.822 --> 24:15.913
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:19.541 --> 24:21.085
[men chuckling]

24:21.085 --> 24:23.295
<i>[tense music]</i>

24:23.295 --> 24:26.590
‐ Well, Stephen,
we have several issues.

24:26.590 --> 24:29.259
The first of which is
the langet is now

24:29.259 --> 24:31.720
completely broken off
of the head.

24:31.720 --> 24:33.263
Held in place by the key.
Nice‐‐

24:33.263 --> 24:35.265
nice idea putting
the key there, by the way.

24:35.265 --> 24:39.728
There's a pretty serious crack
in your handle right here.

24:39.728 --> 24:41.772
Probably because
the langet didn't hold on.

24:41.772 --> 24:42.982
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:42.982 --> 24:44.608
Seth, you're up.
Are you ready?

24:44.608 --> 24:46.777
‐ Yes, sir.

24:46.777 --> 24:47.945
<i>I'm actually pretty nervous.</i>

24:47.945 --> 24:49.863
<i>It's gonna be a brutal test.</i>

24:49.863 --> 24:52.282
I'm hoping
she just holds together.

24:52.282 --> 24:54.118
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:54.118 --> 24:56.954
<i>[heavy metal music]</i>

24:56.954 --> 25:04.086
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:10.968 --> 25:12.302
Oh, yeah.

25:12.302 --> 25:13.846
<i>[tense music]</i>

25:13.846 --> 25:15.973
‐ Seth, this thing's a brute.

25:15.973 --> 25:18.308
The langet here broke.

25:18.308 --> 25:19.685
Could have
used another pin

25:19.685 --> 25:21.520
sort of down
at the bottom here.

25:21.520 --> 25:24.940
The spike is lethal...

25:24.940 --> 25:27.401
but the edge took
a little bit of a roll.

25:27.401 --> 25:29.653
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:29.653 --> 25:32.406
The rest of the blade
is really sharp.

25:32.406 --> 25:34.575
That's a nice axe.
‐ Thank you.

25:34.575 --> 25:36.827
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:36.827 --> 25:39.788
‐ Welcome
to the rope chop trifecta.

25:39.788 --> 25:42.041
To see how sharp your axes are,
I will take your axe

25:42.041 --> 25:45.210
and chop through these ropes,
one thicker than the last.

25:45.210 --> 25:48.922
A well‐balanced, sharp axe
should chop cleanly through.

25:48.922 --> 25:51.341
Anything less,
we just indent, rip,

25:51.341 --> 25:53.886
or worse, do nothing at all.

25:53.886 --> 25:56.221
Jason, you're up first.
You ready for this?

25:56.221 --> 25:58.348
‐ Argh, let's do it.
‐ Let's do it.

25:58.348 --> 26:02.895
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:02.895 --> 26:06.023
<i>[heavy metal music]</i>

26:06.023 --> 26:12.905
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:14.990 --> 26:18.160
<i>[tense music]</i>

26:18.160 --> 26:19.328
All right, Jason.

26:19.328 --> 26:20.746
Your edge over here
is sharp enough

26:20.746 --> 26:22.748
to cut cleanly through
the first rope.

26:22.748 --> 26:25.084
On the second one,
it almost went through

26:25.084 --> 26:26.919
but not quite.

26:26.919 --> 26:29.213
And on the third one,
it cut through about an inch

26:29.213 --> 26:33.050
but most importantly
it's sharp and it will cut.

26:33.050 --> 26:35.219
‐ That's all I wanted to hear.

26:35.219 --> 26:36.553
All right, Stephen,
it's your turn.

26:36.553 --> 26:38.722
You ready for this?
‐ Let's do it.

26:38.722 --> 26:40.224
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:40.224 --> 26:43.769
<i>I've got a broken langet</i>
<i>and there's a crack</i>

26:43.769 --> 26:45.145
<i>in the handle.</i>

26:45.145 --> 26:48.065
I'm feeling a little nervous
that my axe

26:48.065 --> 26:50.234
may not hold together
through this.

26:50.234 --> 26:52.903
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:09.461 --> 27:11.797
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:11.797 --> 27:14.174
‐ Your langet
that broke earlier...

27:14.174 --> 27:16.051
looks like it abandoned ship.

27:16.051 --> 27:18.095
Your handle right here
just split open.

27:18.095 --> 27:21.473
Unfortunately, it's not safe
to continue the test.

27:21.473 --> 27:22.975
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:22.975 --> 27:25.227
‐ Stephen,
your blade has suffered

27:25.227 --> 27:27.312
a catastrophic weapons failure,

27:27.312 --> 27:30.482
but you're not out of
this competition yet.

27:30.482 --> 27:33.569
Seth, your blade
still has to survive

27:33.569 --> 27:36.238
at least the first rope
without failing.

27:36.238 --> 27:38.407
So it would seem like
both of your fates

27:38.407 --> 27:41.869
lie in the hands
of Seth's axe.

27:41.869 --> 27:43.537
<i>‐ We're in sudden death.</i>

27:43.537 --> 27:45.998
One little, itty‐bitty rope
stands between me

27:45.998 --> 27:47.499
and the final round.

27:47.499 --> 27:54.590
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:59.720 --> 28:01.179
‐ Seth, congratulations.

28:01.179 --> 28:02.681
Your blade made it
through one of those ropes

28:02.681 --> 28:04.600
and you're the winner
of this test.

28:04.600 --> 28:06.685
Stephen, unfortunately

28:06.685 --> 28:09.563
that means your blade
didn't make the cut

28:09.563 --> 28:12.190
and I have to ask you
to please leave The Forge.

28:12.190 --> 28:15.027
<i>‐ I'm feeling</i>
<i>a little disappointed.</i>

28:15.027 --> 28:17.029
But I did learn a lot

28:17.029 --> 28:19.197
and it was a great challenge.

28:19.197 --> 28:22.534
I'm gonna do some more axes
and show that I can do them.

28:22.534 --> 28:24.620
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:24.620 --> 28:26.580
‐ Jason, Seth,
congratulations.

28:26.580 --> 28:28.415
Your boarding axes
have earned you a spot

28:28.415 --> 28:29.875
in our finale.

28:29.875 --> 28:31.627
Now we're sending you back
to your home forges

28:31.627 --> 28:33.712
to recreate an iconic weapon
from history.

28:33.712 --> 28:35.339
That weapon is...

28:35.339 --> 28:39.259
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:39.259 --> 28:41.553
Black Beard's
infamous cutlass.

28:41.553 --> 28:42.888
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:42.888 --> 28:44.181
‐ [exhales]

28:44.181 --> 28:46.058
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:46.058 --> 28:48.936
<i>Among the most notorious</i>
<i>pirates of the 18th century,</i>

28:48.936 --> 28:50.646
<i>Black Beard terrorized</i>
<i>Caribbean</i>

28:50.646 --> 28:52.272
<i>and Atlantic merchant shipping</i>

28:52.272 --> 28:53.941
<i>with his trademark cutlass</i>
<i>in hand.</i>

28:53.941 --> 28:55.651
<i>Its short but</i>
<i>thick‐curved blade featured</i>

28:55.651 --> 28:57.569
<i>a razor‐sharp edge</i>
<i>that was ideal for hacking</i>

28:57.569 --> 28:59.655
<i>and slashing during</i>
<i>close‐quarters combat</i>

28:59.655 --> 29:01.406
<i>while seizing small vessels.</i>

29:01.406 --> 29:03.784
<i>In his legendary battle</i>
<i>with Captain Robert Maynard</i>

29:03.784 --> 29:07.412
<i>in 1718, Black Beard's cutlass</i>
<i>broke Maynard's sword in half</i>

29:07.412 --> 29:09.081
<i>with a single blow.</i>

29:09.081 --> 29:10.958
<i>Today Black Beard's</i>
<i>menacing presence</i>

29:10.958 --> 29:12.292
<i>and expert swordsmanship</i>

29:12.292 --> 29:14.294
<i>can still be seen</i>
<i>in the videogame</i>

29:14.294 --> 29:16.755
<i>"Assassin's Creed IV:</i>
<i>Black Flag."</i>

29:16.755 --> 29:18.256
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:18.256 --> 29:20.425
Your blades must fall within
the following parameters.

29:20.425 --> 29:22.928
Your blade must include
a fuller on both sides,

29:22.928 --> 29:24.888
must be sharpened
on a single edge,

29:24.888 --> 29:26.890
and it must include
a clip point.

29:26.890 --> 29:29.685
Now we're gonna get into
the handle details.

29:29.685 --> 29:31.520
<i>You must have a pommel,</i>
<i>a knuckle bow,</i>

29:31.520 --> 29:33.939
<i>a right side bar guard,</i>
<i>a rear quillion,</i>

29:33.939 --> 29:37.609
<i>and a symmetrical, perforated,</i>
<i>double‐clam‐shell guard.</i>

29:37.609 --> 29:41.780
‐ The whole handle
is full of names and things

29:41.780 --> 29:44.282
<i>that I've never heard of</i>
<i>so I think there's gonna be</i>

29:44.282 --> 29:46.451
<i>a lot of</i>
<i>challenges to it but...</i>

29:46.451 --> 29:48.453
it's one of the coolest things
I've ever seen.

29:48.453 --> 29:49.788
I'm excited.

29:49.788 --> 29:51.415
‐ You will have five days
at your home forge

29:51.415 --> 29:52.958
to complete this challenge.

29:52.958 --> 29:55.127
At the end of five days,
you will return and present

29:55.127 --> 29:57.004
your weapons
to our panel of expert judges.

29:57.004 --> 29:59.965
Only after they've tested them
and inspected your work

29:59.965 --> 30:01.633
will they declare one of you
our next

30:01.633 --> 30:03.093
"Forged in Fire" champion

30:03.093 --> 30:05.220
who leaves here with
that check for ten grand.

30:05.220 --> 30:07.973
Good luck.
We'll see you in five days.

30:07.973 --> 30:10.767
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:10.767 --> 30:14.062
<i>‐ I'm feeling pretty excited</i>
<i>to be back in my home forge.</i>

30:14.062 --> 30:15.522
Today I'm gonna be
making two different

30:15.522 --> 30:16.982
kinds of damascus.

30:16.982 --> 30:18.984
<i>I've never made a weapon</i>
<i>of this caliber.</i>

30:18.984 --> 30:20.485
<i>This size.</i>

30:20.485 --> 30:22.654
<i>And I've never done</i>
<i>any kind of knuckle bow</i>

30:22.654 --> 30:24.156
<i>or de guard.</i>

30:24.156 --> 30:26.575
I have
a huge chunk of steel here,

30:26.575 --> 30:27.743
that's for sure.

30:27.743 --> 30:31.163
The judges
really hit on the handle

30:31.163 --> 30:32.956
<i>and weight distribution.</i>

30:32.956 --> 30:34.875
<i>I'm gonna make sure that</i>
<i>the handles aren't too big</i>

30:34.875 --> 30:36.293
<i>but they're not too small,</i>
<i>because</i>

30:36.293 --> 30:38.962
there will be
multiple operators.

30:38.962 --> 30:42.007
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:42.007 --> 30:43.925
<i>‐ So it's the start</i>
<i>of day one</i>

30:43.925 --> 30:45.677
and I cannot wait
to get started on

30:45.677 --> 30:47.554
Black Beard's
legendary cutlass.

30:47.554 --> 30:50.682
<i>I've never built anything</i>
<i>like this, not even close,</i>

30:50.682 --> 30:52.225
So I'm gonna be
making most of it up

30:52.225 --> 30:53.769
as I go along.

30:53.769 --> 30:55.937
<i>Plan for day one,</i>
<i>I definitely want to have</i>

30:55.937 --> 30:57.939
<i>the blade shaped out,</i>
<i>formed out.</i>

30:57.939 --> 30:59.316
I want to have
the fullers done.

30:59.316 --> 31:00.859
I wanna have
the rough grind done.

31:00.859 --> 31:02.360
So I'm using
this guillotine tool

31:02.360 --> 31:06.031
to try and get
these fullers forged in.

31:06.031 --> 31:08.075
I have no press,
no power hammers.

31:08.075 --> 31:10.368
My power hammer's‐‐
look at that.

31:10.368 --> 31:12.037
Huh?
This is the problem.

31:12.037 --> 31:14.206
You get an arm like that
and one like that.

31:14.206 --> 31:16.249
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:16.249 --> 31:17.834
<i>‐ I did the heat treat.</i>

31:17.834 --> 31:19.377
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:19.377 --> 31:21.880
<i>Today, I want to work</i>
<i>on the handle.</i>

31:21.880 --> 31:24.466
I've never put a guard together
like this ever.

31:24.466 --> 31:26.218
<i>Getting all</i>
<i>the measurements right</i>

31:26.218 --> 31:27.928
<i>is just guess work.</i>

31:27.928 --> 31:30.472
<i>I'm doing damascus</i>
<i>for all the handle pieces.</i>

31:30.472 --> 31:33.308
<i>I want all of it</i>
<i>to be uniform.</i>

31:33.308 --> 31:36.061
Something's out of place
or out of whack or out of tune

31:36.061 --> 31:38.730
or out of twist,
it's not gonna work.

31:38.730 --> 31:41.066
It's a lot of steel
to be putting on a handle.

31:41.066 --> 31:42.150
Yeah.

31:42.150 --> 31:43.610
<i>I hope that the amount of steel</i>

31:43.610 --> 31:45.654
<i>on the weapon</i>
<i>won't make it too heavy.</i>

31:45.654 --> 31:47.948
Black Beard just might as well
just throw it in the water

31:47.948 --> 31:49.699
and use it as an anchor.

31:49.699 --> 31:51.243
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:51.243 --> 31:55.080
‐ Start of day three,
the blade is out of tempering.

31:55.080 --> 31:56.581
Looking really good.

31:56.581 --> 31:59.251
<i>But there's a ton of work</i>
<i>to do today.</i>

31:59.251 --> 32:02.170
It's gonna be
forging the handle parts.

32:02.170 --> 32:05.215
I'm gonna go through
my scrap pile to find steel.

32:05.215 --> 32:07.592
It's probably just gonna be
some kind of mild steel

32:07.592 --> 32:11.721
<i>and the plan is to take it</i>
<i>one piece at a time</i>

32:11.721 --> 32:15.559
and forge it as if I was
forging a jigsaw puzzle.

32:15.559 --> 32:18.019
<i>The guard bone's connected</i>
<i>to the knuckle bow bone</i>

32:18.019 --> 32:20.230
<i>is connected to</i>
<i>the rear quillion bone.</i>

32:20.230 --> 32:23.733
It's gonna be an interesting
forging process.

32:23.733 --> 32:26.653
Even though it's gonna be
cheesy and campy,

32:26.653 --> 32:29.406
I'm making the clam shell guard
look like clam shell.

32:29.406 --> 32:31.616
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:31.616 --> 32:35.245
‐ This morning, I've got a lot
of grinding to do on the blade

32:35.245 --> 32:37.122
and shaping the handle.

32:37.122 --> 32:39.833
<i>I wanna do</i>
<i>a robust edge on it.</i>

32:39.833 --> 32:41.585
<i>I wanna keep it thick</i>

32:41.585 --> 32:43.628
<i>so it doesn't</i>
<i>get broke up so easily.</i>

32:43.628 --> 32:46.798
I bent my guard out
to get the heat treat right

32:46.798 --> 32:48.967
and now I gotta
bend it back in.

32:48.967 --> 32:50.635
We'll see how good
my temper is.

32:50.635 --> 32:54.472
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:54.472 --> 32:55.473
[metal clacks]

32:55.473 --> 32:56.641
Ooh.

32:56.641 --> 32:58.643
[bleep]

32:58.643 --> 32:59.060
Son of a gun.

33:02.439 --> 33:05.108
I just broke my knuckle bow.

33:05.108 --> 33:07.986
This is not how
to get into the final day.

33:07.986 --> 33:09.487
Well, it's hard.

33:09.487 --> 33:12.616
<i>I think it's gonna be</i>
<i>a pretty good struggle</i>

33:12.616 --> 33:14.242
<i>trying to get it together.</i>

33:14.242 --> 33:18.622
<i>What I'm gonna do is</i>
<i>shorten out my knuckle bow,</i>

33:18.622 --> 33:22.792
<i>get it into position</i>
<i>to where I need it.</i>

33:22.792 --> 33:26.046
Maybe breaking it was
a blessing in disguise.

33:26.046 --> 33:27.797
<i>I got to rework</i>
<i>the knuckle bow</i>

33:27.797 --> 33:30.508
<i>the way I wanted it</i>
<i>to make it prettier.</i>

33:30.508 --> 33:32.636
I like it.

33:32.636 --> 33:35.847
My sword is all together.
It's all one piece now.

33:35.847 --> 33:38.308
It's a cutlass.
It's Black Beard's cutlass.

33:38.308 --> 33:39.976
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:39.976 --> 33:42.145
Heavy...ish.

33:42.145 --> 33:44.314
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:44.314 --> 33:47.025
<i>‐ Start of day five</i>
<i>and not much to do</i>

33:47.025 --> 33:49.027
just a little bit more
finishing work

33:49.027 --> 33:51.112
and I'm feeling pretty good.

33:51.112 --> 33:53.823
<i>Putting the jigsaw puzzle</i>
<i>of my handle together</i>

33:53.823 --> 33:55.367
<i>went really well.</i>

33:55.367 --> 33:58.161
<i>I put a little skull face</i>
<i>on the back there.</i>

33:58.161 --> 34:00.038
I'm gonna leave
the edge geometry

34:00.038 --> 34:02.707
just a little beefier
just so it can stand up to

34:02.707 --> 34:05.877
some of the brutal chopping
that it's probably gonna see.

34:05.877 --> 34:08.463
Ye stole my pirate booty...

34:08.463 --> 34:10.674
and now you're
paying the price.

34:10.674 --> 34:13.301
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:13.301 --> 34:15.512
It will kill.

34:15.512 --> 34:18.098
<i>[tense music]</i>

34:18.098 --> 34:20.809
‐ Jason, Seth.
You fellas have had five days

34:20.809 --> 34:25.105
at your home forges to work on
your Black Beard's cutlasses.

34:25.105 --> 34:27.899
Jason, tell us a little bit
about your blade.

34:27.899 --> 34:31.361
‐ My blade is made out of
5160 spring steel.

34:31.361 --> 34:33.571
<i>The guard parts are</i>
<i>all just mild steel</i>

34:33.571 --> 34:34.739
<i>out of my scrap bin.</i>

34:34.739 --> 34:35.782
<i>And I used a railroad spike</i>

34:35.782 --> 34:37.284
<i>to do the skull pommel.</i>

34:37.284 --> 34:39.577
I'm excited to see
what it can do.

34:39.577 --> 34:42.414
I'm also scared that
you're gonna destroy it.

34:42.414 --> 34:44.708
‐ All right, well,
right next to you, Seth,

34:44.708 --> 34:46.501
tell the judges
about your weapon.

34:46.501 --> 34:49.754
<i>‐ I constructed my blade out</i>
<i>of 1095 and 15N20.</i>

34:49.754 --> 34:52.299
<i>And all the handle pieces out</i>
<i>of 1095</i>

34:52.299 --> 34:54.092
<i>and 201 nickel sheeting.</i>

34:54.092 --> 34:57.637
<i>The billet for the blade</i>
<i>was 38 layers of damascus.</i>

34:57.637 --> 34:59.556
I am proud of my blade.

34:59.556 --> 35:02.851
‐ All right, gents, well,
this is the main event.

35:02.851 --> 35:05.312
And up first, the kill test.
Doug.

35:05.312 --> 35:07.689
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:07.689 --> 35:11.067
‐ Bladesmiths, to test
the lethality of your cutlass,

35:11.067 --> 35:12.485
I'm going to
inflict lethal wounds

35:12.485 --> 35:14.237
on these ballistic dummies.

35:14.237 --> 35:15.780
Jason, you're up first.
You ready?

35:15.780 --> 35:18.575
‐ I sure hope so, Doug.
‐ Let's do this.

35:18.575 --> 35:25.457
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:25.457 --> 35:28.752
<i>[heavy metal music]</i>

35:28.752 --> 35:35.634
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:46.519 --> 35:49.272
<i>[tense music]</i>

35:49.272 --> 35:51.775
All right, Jason, you've
got a very big handle here.

35:51.775 --> 35:53.943
But at least
it's got the swells.

35:53.943 --> 35:55.654
It's got an indexing
to when I hold onto it,

35:55.654 --> 35:57.614
I can tell where the edge is.

35:57.614 --> 36:00.116
The weight that you have
in this weapon is so light

36:00.116 --> 36:03.119
in a sense that I can wield it
even around here.

36:03.119 --> 36:05.455
You cut the clavicle
into the ribs

36:05.455 --> 36:07.374
all the way through the lungs.

36:07.374 --> 36:11.002
And definitely it will kill.

36:11.002 --> 36:12.587
‐ All I ever wanted to hear.

36:12.587 --> 36:13.838
You made my day.

36:13.838 --> 36:15.674
‐ Seth, you're up next.
You ready?

36:15.674 --> 36:18.134
‐ Get some.

36:18.134 --> 36:22.305
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:22.305 --> 36:25.642
<i>[heavy metal music]</i>

36:25.642 --> 36:32.732
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:40.156 --> 36:47.080
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:48.039 --> 36:50.375
‐ [indistinct]
[chuckles]

36:50.375 --> 36:53.545
‐ All right, Seth.
You're sword is forward heavy

36:53.545 --> 36:55.171
without a balance coming back.

36:55.171 --> 36:57.048
I don't know who's shoulder's
gonna hurt more.

36:57.048 --> 36:58.591
The dummy's or mine.

36:58.591 --> 37:01.553
But your weapon, sir,
will kill.

37:01.553 --> 37:03.346
‐ Thank you.

37:03.346 --> 37:05.390
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:05.390 --> 37:08.226
‐ To test the strength
and durability of your swords,

37:08.226 --> 37:09.978
I'll be chopping
through these bones

37:09.978 --> 37:11.646
and then attacking
that peg leg.

37:11.646 --> 37:14.899
Now remember this test is not
about what your blades

37:14.899 --> 37:16.526
do to these targets,

37:16.526 --> 37:18.820
it's about what these targets
do to your blades.

37:18.820 --> 37:20.155
Jason, you're up.
Are you ready?

37:20.155 --> 37:23.032
‐ Nope.
‐ [soft laugh]

37:23.032 --> 37:24.534
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:24.534 --> 37:25.869
‐ [sighs]

37:25.869 --> 37:29.038
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:29.038 --> 37:32.125
<i>[heavy metal music]</i>

37:32.125 --> 37:39.215
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:48.600 --> 37:50.393
<i>[tense music]</i>

37:50.393 --> 37:53.438
‐ The balance of your weapon
is really nice...

37:53.438 --> 37:55.732
Which is surprising
because you've made

37:55.732 --> 37:57.734
a two‐handed cutlass.

37:57.734 --> 38:01.613
Your blade held up very well
except for the one little chip

38:01.613 --> 38:03.615
and it's not even a chip,
it's a roll.

38:03.615 --> 38:06.075
So it didn't blow out.
It's a good job.

38:06.075 --> 38:07.327
‐ Thank you, Dave.

38:07.327 --> 38:08.912
‐ All right, Seth,
are you ready?

38:08.912 --> 38:11.414
‐ Yes, sir.

38:11.414 --> 38:15.126
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:15.126 --> 38:18.087
<i>[heavy metal music]</i>

38:18.087 --> 38:25.136
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:30.517 --> 38:32.602
<i>[tense music]</i>

38:32.602 --> 38:34.103
‐ All right, Seth.

38:34.103 --> 38:36.981
First up, this thing's a beast.

38:36.981 --> 38:41.694
It is probably a pound heavier
than your competitor's sword.

38:41.694 --> 38:45.615
Your blade, I can run
my fingernail down this.

38:45.615 --> 38:48.159
I can see a couple
of glinting spots...

38:48.159 --> 38:49.953
but it really didn't
take any damage.

38:49.953 --> 38:52.622
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:52.622 --> 38:54.833
‐ All right, bladesmiths,
let's find out

38:54.833 --> 38:56.292
if there's any edge left.

38:56.292 --> 38:59.170
This is the rope cut
and pirate sail slash.

38:59.170 --> 39:00.797
To test the edge
of your cutlass,

39:00.797 --> 39:03.466
I will cut this rope
which will raise the sail

39:03.466 --> 39:05.885
and then I will slash the sail.

39:05.885 --> 39:08.346
This is all about
what your sword

39:08.346 --> 39:10.849
will do to the sail and rope.

39:10.849 --> 39:12.475
Jason, you're up first.
Ready?

39:12.475 --> 39:14.477
‐ Yes, sir.

39:14.477 --> 39:16.479
<i>I'm a little nervous</i>
<i>going into this sharpness test</i>

39:16.479 --> 39:19.274
'cause I think it's gonna
come down to this test.

39:19.274 --> 39:21.734
<i>I think I'm a little bit ahead</i>
<i>on the kill test.</i>

39:21.734 --> 39:24.654
<i>Seth is a little bit ahead</i>
<i>on the strength test.</i>

39:24.654 --> 39:26.990
Winner take all on this one.

39:26.990 --> 39:27.490
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:31.035 --> 39:34.080
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:34.080 --> 39:37.458
<i>[heavy metal music]</i>

39:37.458 --> 39:44.465
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:47.093 --> 39:49.053
<i>[tense music]</i>

39:49.053 --> 39:50.722
‐ Arrr‐righty, Jason.

39:50.722 --> 39:53.391
Your edge cut through
the rope easily

39:53.391 --> 39:56.227
and cuts with every part
that the edge met

39:56.227 --> 39:57.812
on this pirate sail.

39:57.812 --> 40:01.900
Overall, sir,
your sword will cut.

40:01.900 --> 40:02.942
‐ Awesome.

40:02.942 --> 40:04.235
‐ Seth, how you feeling?

40:04.235 --> 40:05.695
‐ Feeling good.
Let's go.

40:05.695 --> 40:07.989
‐ Let's do this.

40:07.989 --> 40:14.787
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:22.086 --> 40:28.468
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:30.929 --> 40:32.263
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:32.263 --> 40:34.265
All right, Seth.
What are the chances

40:34.265 --> 40:37.602
you find a very dull spot
on the first cut on the rope.

40:37.602 --> 40:38.811
But on the second cut,

40:38.811 --> 40:40.647
I had found another spot
that was sharp.

40:40.647 --> 40:42.148
But on the sail

40:42.148 --> 40:45.944
working a heavy sword
like this, affects my cuts.

40:45.944 --> 40:49.739
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:49.739 --> 40:51.824
‐ Jason, Seth,
the judges have

40:51.824 --> 40:53.034
tested your weapons

40:53.034 --> 40:55.203
and they've made
a final decision.

40:55.203 --> 40:58.122
Our new
"Forged in Fire" champion is...

40:58.122 --> 41:00.458
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:00.458 --> 41:02.126
Jason.

41:02.126 --> 41:05.296
Congratulations, you're the new
"Forged in Fire" champion.

41:05.296 --> 41:08.466
Seth, unfortunately, your blade
did not make the cut.

41:08.466 --> 41:11.636
‐ Seth, your weapon
was significantly heavier

41:11.636 --> 41:14.013
and it had a stout edge
that underperformed

41:14.013 --> 41:15.473
on the sharpness test.

41:15.473 --> 41:17.809
For that reason,
we're sending you home.

41:17.809 --> 41:19.811
‐ Seth,
please surrender your blade.

41:19.811 --> 41:21.312
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:21.312 --> 41:22.814
<i>‐ No regrets, man.</i>

41:22.814 --> 41:25.149
<i>I think I made</i>
<i>an exceptional blade</i>

41:25.149 --> 41:26.985
<i>but it is what it is,</i>
<i>you know?</i>

41:26.985 --> 41:29.988
Elimination's elimination.
That's the name of the game.

41:29.988 --> 41:32.991
I'm proud of myself
but I don't feel as good

41:32.991 --> 41:34.826
as I would have if I had won.

41:34.826 --> 41:37.870
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:37.870 --> 41:40.081
‐ Jason, congratulations,
you arrr our new

41:40.081 --> 41:42.208
"Forged in Fire" champion
and that's a title

41:42.208 --> 41:45.378
that comes with a bundle of
bullion that's worth ten grand.

41:45.378 --> 41:47.505
How you feeling right now?
‐ [laughs]

41:47.505 --> 41:50.717
I mean, come on.
That's incredible.

41:50.717 --> 41:54.012
‐ Please present your blade
to the judges.

41:54.012 --> 41:57.015
‐ What?
"Forged in Fire" champion.

41:57.015 --> 41:58.975
<i>I don't know how to respond</i>
<i>'cause I never</i>

41:58.975 --> 42:01.519
expected
to be here saying that.

42:01.519 --> 42:02.979
<i>♪ ♪</i>

42:02.979 --> 42:04.522
I don't know.
[laughs]

42:04.522 --> 42:05.982
<i>♪ ♪</i>

42:05.982 --> 42:07.442
What?
What do you want from me?

42:07.442 --> 42:12.238
<i>♪ ♪</i>

42:12.238 --> 42:14.365
<i>[echoing slam]</i>
